{
  "text": "Supernatants of transformed ST cell clones had virus titers that were Ͻ10 2 PFU/ml, very low in comparison with the 10 7 PFU/ml observed in untransformed cells under the same conditions. The decrease in virus titer probably was not due to a nonspecific reduction in the capacity of the transformed cells to produce virus, since the transformed ST cells produced VSV as efficiently as the untransformed cells. In addition, the TGEV titers were more similar in the supernatants of cell lines in which only 10 to 15% of the cells were transformed than in the cloned transformed cell lines in which 100% of the cells were antibody producers. The most likely explanation for this residual virus persistence is that TGEV neutralization is reversible and at the antibody concentrations present in the supernatants of the rMAb-transformed cells a small virus fraction (10 2 to 10 3 PFU/ml) remains as free infectious virus while most of the virus (10 4 to 10 5 PFU/ml) is in the form of noninfectious virus-antibody complexes [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "1880581"
